Well, I'd be surprised if the idea of the Archive is in the original application. I think it came to us fairly early on in doing the field-work. Yes ... but then we'd started, we realised that there was that potential. And it has, actual
ly, been used by a number of interesting people. There was Standish Meacham, who, almost as soon as we'd finished, who ... American social historian, who wrote a book called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Worlds Apart}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 , which is three-quarters or more taken from our Archive: it's a social history book about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And then another rather important one with John Gillis, who wrote on the history of marriage in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 [For Better, For Worse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 ], and there are, I think, three chapters from our Archive. And then there was one by Charles More, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Skill and the English Working-Class}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 , where we are again, the major source. There are a lot of people who have used it in a slightly lesser way, and there's a whole book on education based on it fairly
 recently, too. And this work on social mobility, too, which is recent. So it's a continuing source of value. That's in spite of the fact that until very recently, it was not being looked after, formally, by anyone. Brenda kept a watching eye over it, but
 
it wasn't officially open at all. People would learn there might be a possibility and then write. But I think that it's going to of tremendous value in the future, because it's absolutely unique. You couldn't possibly do it any longer, there are interview
s going back to people born in the 1870s.
