\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid8224390\charrsid15550915 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Well, we had the original set of material [for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
The Edwardians}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 ], and that had been archived properly, and we also archived the upper-class families. And then the East Anglian fishermen, we sent to a maritime museum in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Yarmouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But I didn't know what to do with the fishing material, so we kept the tapes at Essex, but we did send copies to these various archives in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, over the years. And we never had the money to transcribe properly for that. Not full transcriptions, no. No. Some of it is transcribed, but quite a lot is not.
