No, no, no, this was ... I think we explained that earlier, this was a n
ew set of interviews where we put together the field work for Life Stories and Ageing, with Families and Social Mobility. And what we did was, we took a sample from another study [the Stagflation study by Howard Newby, Graham Marshall and David Rose], of 
people in their middle years, in their thirties, forties, early fifties \endash 
 [we interviewed] over a hundred of them, 120 [families altogether because there was a deliberate over-representation of Scotland], but I used a hundred for the analysis. [After interv
iewing the middle generation informant selected from the sample], we then tried to interview an older person, the grandparent generation, and a child. Actually, in practice, often we weren't able to do that, because either the older ones had died, or the 
c
hildren were too young. So that proved not possible to do all the time, but we did it for a lot of them. And, of course, it was very interesting when we were able to. And it helped to develop the theory for understanding the families, which then one could
 use. Even when you had a single [middle generation interview only], you could begin to see what the [traansgenerational] relationships were as well. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10361243 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915  
