\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Part Three: }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12977908\charrsid15550915 Interview held on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid4794045 16 June 2002}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Karen:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 We're going to talk about the research project, "}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 On the Edge of Later Life - life stories and ageing in late middle age}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 ". It started in 1992.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1836035\charrsid15550915 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Well, this was a project that I was invited to undertake, because the [Economic and Social] Research Counci
l had a research initiative on ageing, and they wanted a qualitative in-depth research project. It picked up some of the ideas that came out of the Life Stories and Ageing project, the idea that you had to draw on the resources you had developed in early 
l
ife or middle life, in order to have a successful later life. And so we thought we'd look at the end of the middle life period to see whether people were looking forward to later life, retirement, and so on, or not. And we did 50 interviews, in-depth ones
, very much on the same model [with men and women aged 55-60]. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Karen:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 How did you get the sample?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1836035\charrsid15550915 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
Well, this was another instance where we wanted to link up with a quantitative study. So we went to the British Household Panel Study, which is also at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}
, and originally, I had thought that we might be able to link up with their main sample. But eventually, we were given part of their pilot sample, and, in fact, it turned out to be slightly disappointing, because there was an over-represent
ation of middle-class people in this pilot, and so we had rather a struggle, actually, to get a satisfactory number of working-class informants. So anyway, apart from that difficulty, we designed an interview schedule very much on the same lines as the ot
h
er projects, particularly close to the Life Stories and Ageing one, but obviously with the focus more on preparing for retirement and later life. We published very little, because Rebecca Abrams, who was the research officer, had really just finished the 
i
nterviewing by the time the project finished, and so we did a report on it, but I had hoped to do an article with quotations from the interviews, and I hope we still will, but she has been very preoccupied with other work, and also she had a baby. So that
 hasn't happened. There's been no outcome, at the moment. So this research has been among the less successful ones, I suppose, along with the car workers. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15550915 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
What emerged was a bit disappointing, which was that incredibly few people really were looking forwa
rd at all. There were, basically, typically two groups. There were the majority who were still at work, and weren't thinking of retirement, were just trying to carry on, and were totally absorbed in their current situation, and I think it was almost, actu
ally, it was a taboo thought, what they would do later. And the others were the ones who'd been forced into [retirement] by unemployment or ill-health. And they tended to be rather miserable people, rather depressed\'85 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10361243 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15550915 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 I was interested by some of the litera
ture on preparing for retirement and so on, and talked to Chris Phillipson, at Keele, about this, and I could see that this was something that could be usefully got into, really, planning for a creative later life. And there didn't seem to be nearly enoug
h help for people who were thinking that way. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10361243 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15550915 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
Because, basically, because of the taboo, the stigma against old age, which was one of the things that came out from Life Stories and Ageing, where it was a major feeling. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 I Don't Feel Old
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 , well, one reason [f
or the title] is that you can't feel a really okay person if you feel old. Because old people are [seen as] ill, stupid, they've lost their ability to do this, that, lost their memory, lost their joie de vivre and all those things, and the image of a pers
o
n functioning normally, because of a stigma, doesn't include an older person. And that's, again, the reason why people can't think ahead, towards being old. They just can't bear the thought of being like that. I think that people are victims of ... I thin
k it's an appalling social stigma, really, old age, in a society which focuses so much on the ideals of youth and beauty. I could see that one could have got into that, but I think we hadn't got the energy, really, to take that further.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10361243 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Karen:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Did you see anything about the relation between the person and his or her family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15550915\charrsid15550915 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
Well, there was a bit about that. We got the material, but it hasn't been very thoroughly analysed, I must say, that side of it. Certainly, it\rquote s quite interesting how, when men re
tire, there's a problem for the women, if the women have not been working, of household space, there's a problem of having the men around, renegotiating space and roles. And there is the material there to write something on that. But we haven't done it ye
t.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 Karen:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 So the outcome is a paper?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15550915\charrsid15550915 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10361243\charrsid15550915 
Just the report. And then there was the idea, because really, the basic notion about the research was to predict that people who were making more preparation and a more positive approach to retirement, were going
 to do better when they retired, and so the way, of course, of testing that, would be to do a further survey later. So we kept the information, so that we could keep in touch with the people. But again, I'm not at all sure that it's likely to be done. And
 
it would be interesting, but I somehow feel it'll probably fall by the wayside. I suppose one could just think of those interviews as a resource, which, hopefully, will be used. They're another of the set that have gone through Qualidata, to the National 
Sound Archive, the tapes and the transcripts.
